chat_message.content:
Website Development Proposal

1. High-Level Architecture
• Presentation Layer (React/Next.js SPA) – Server-side rendered pages for SEO, delivered via edge CDN (CloudFront) with automatic image and asset optimization.  
• API Layer – Stateless REST + GraphQL services in Node.js (Express + Apollo). Containers run in Kubernetes with horizontal auto-scaling, blue/green deploy, and roll-back.  
• Data Layer – PostgreSQL 15 for transactions (users, orders, products, payments, inventory) plus Redis for session + product-cache; S3 object storage for media.  
• Security – OAuth2/OIDC (Auth0/Keycloak), HTTPS everywhere, JWT, WAF, rate-limiting, and encryption at rest for DB and S3.  
• DevOps – GitHub Actions → Docker build → Terraform → EKS/GKE deploy; versioned IaC, CI/CD gates, automated tests.

2. Detailed Database Design (PostgreSQL, 3NF)
• users (id PK, email, password_hash, role, created_at)  
• addresses (id PK, user_id FK, …)  
• products (id PK, sku, name, description, price, inventory_qty, category_id FK)  
• categories (id PK, parent_id FK NULLABLE, name, slug)  
• product_images (id PK, product_id FK, url, sort_order)  
• carts (id PK, user_id FK, status, updated_at)  
• cart_items (cart_id PK/FK, product_id PK/FK, qty)  
• orders (id PK, user_id FK, total, status, payment_intent, created_at)  
• order_items (order_id PK/FK, product_id PK/FK, qty, price_snapshot)  
• payments (id PK, order_id FK, provider, amount, status)  
• reviews (id PK, user_id FK, product_id FK, rating, comment, created_at)  
Indexes: lower(email) UNIQUE, sku UNIQUE, GIN on product name + description for search, composite indexes on (user_id, status) etc.  
Redis keys: session:<id>, product:<id>, cart:<userId>.

3. Technology Stack
Frontend: React 18, Next.js 13 (app router), TypeScript, TailwindCSS, Redux Toolkit, SWR, Jest/RTL, Playwright.  
Backend: Node.js 18, Express, Apollo GraphQL, TypeScript, Prisma ORM.  
Infrastructure: Docker, Kubernetes (EKS/GKE), NGINX Ingress, AWS S3, CloudFront, Redis 7, PostgreSQL RDS, Terraform IaC.  
Observability: Prometheus + Grafana (metrics), Loki & ELK (logs), Jaeger (tracing), Sentry (errors).  

4. Hardware / Cloud Sizing
Staging: 2× t3.medium API, 1× db.t3.medium DB, small Redis.  
Production kick-off: 3× m5.large API (autoscale 3-12), RDS db.m5.large Multi-AZ (100 GB SSD), cache.m5.large Redis, 500 GB S3 storage, 2× t3.medium monitoring stack.  

5. User-Experience (UX) Optimization
• Mobile-first responsive design, WCAG 2.1 AA accessibility.  
• Fast first paint: SSR, adaptive image formats (WebP/AVIF), HTTP/2 push, critical-CSS inlined, bundle splitting & lazy-loaded routes.  
• Perceived speed: skeleton screens, optimistic UI on cart/checkout, background prefetch.  
• Search with autocompletion and typo-tolerance.  
• Personalization: real-time recommendations using Redis streams / analytics pipeline.  
• Micro-interactions & subtle animations (Framer Motion) to increase engagement.  
• Dark-mode toggle with OS-level preference detection.  
• Progressive Web App (PWA) for offline browsing of cached content.

6. Testing & Quality
Unit (Jest), integration (Supertest), E2E (Playwright), accessibility (axe), performance (Lighthouse CI). Code coverage gate ≥ 90 %.  
Security scans (Snyk, OWASP ZAP) in CI.  
Load tests with k6; target P95 API latency < 200 ms and LCP < 2.5 s.  

7. Performance & Scalability Plan
• API statelessness + Kubernetes HPA for pods.  
• PostgreSQL read replicas when needed.  
• Redis caching for hot data; CloudFront edge caching for assets/html.  
• Queue (SNS/SQS or RabbitMQ) for async tasks (emails, webhooks).  
• Regular DB index audit, query plan monitoring.  

8. Deployment & Rollback
GitHub Actions pipeline: build, test, SCA, container push → Terraform plan/apply → Kubernetes rolling update with blue/green strategy and automated health checks. Instant rollback on failure.  

9. Maintenance & Monitoring
• Prometheus alerts on latency, error rate, CPU/memory.  
• Grafana dashboards, Sentry error triage.  
• Weekly vulnerability patching; monthly UX/Bounce-rate review (Hotjar, GA).  
• Quarterly scalability test & cost-optimization review.  

Deliverables
• Detailed system architecture diagrams (C4-level).  
• ER diagram and migration scripts (Prisma).  
• UI component library in Storybook.  
• CI/CD pipeline definition (GitHub Actions + Terraform).  
• Comprehensive test suite and monitoring dashboards.  

Timeline
Week 1-2: Requirements & wireframes.  
Week 3-5: Architecture, DB schema, CI/CD setup.  
Week 6-10: Frontend & API MVP, unit/integration tests.  
Week 11-13: E2E tests, performance tuning, accessibility audit.  
Week 14: UAT, soft launch.  

This proposal provides a scalable, secure, and performant foundation along with concrete UX optimization and testing strategies to ensure an outstanding e-commerce website experience.

Here are some popular halal-friendly recipe ideas along with the nutritional breakdown of their key ingredients. This will help you gauge both compliance with halal guidelines and overall nutrition as you plan your Canadian halal food venture.

1. Halal Chicken Biryani
   • Basic method: Marinate halal-certified chicken in yogurt and spices (cumin, coriander, turmeric, etc.), sauté with onions, tomatoes and ginger-garlic paste, layer with par-cooked basmati rice, then steam (“dum”) until fragrant.  
   • Key halal points:  
     – Use poultry from a certified halal supplier.  
     – Verify all spice blends contain no alcohol-based extracts or animal-derived anti-caking agents.  
     – Yogurt cultures must be microbial (not animal rennet).  

2. Halal Beef Shawarma
   • Basic method: Marinate thinly sliced halal beef in a spice mix with garlic, vinegar or lemon juice, then grill/roast and shave. Serve in pita with lettuce, tomatoes, cucumber, garlic sauce, and fresh coriander.  
   • Key halal points:  
     – Beef must be hand-slaughtered to Canadian halal standards (e.g., HMA, ISNA certification).  
     – Vinegar/lemon juice are fine; avoid wine or malt-extract marinades.  
     – Ensure garlic sauce (often toum) contains no alcohol or non-halal emulsifiers.  

Nutritional snapshot of core ingredients (per 100 g)  
– Basmati Rice: 356 cal, 7.9 g protein, 78 g carbs, 0.6 g fat, 1.0 g fiber  
– Halal Chicken (skinless): 165 cal, 31 g protein, 0 g carbs, 3.6 g fat  
– Halal Beef (lean): 250 cal, 26 g protein, 0 g carbs, 15 g fat  
– Yogurt (plain, 2 %): 59 cal, 10 g protein, 3.6 g carbs, 0.4 g fat  
– Onions: 40 cal, 1.1 g protein, 9.3 g carbs, 0.1 g fat, 1.7 g fiber  
– Tomatoes: 18 cal, 0.9 g protein, 3.9 g carbs, 0.2 g fat, 1.2 g fiber  
– Lettuce: 15 cal, 1.4 g protein, 3 g carbs, 0.2 g fat, 1.3 g fiber  
– Cucumber: 16 cal, 0.7 g protein, 4 g carbs, 0.1 g fat, 0.5 g fiber  
– Fresh Coriander: 23 cal, 2.1 g protein, 3.7 g carbs, 0.5 g fat  
– Garlic Sauce (toum): 180 cal, 2 g protein, 12 g carbs, 14 g fat  
– Ginger-Garlic Paste: 125 cal, 6 g protein, 28 g carbs, 1 g fat  
– Pita Bread: 275 cal, 9 g protein, 55 g carbs, 1 g fat  
– Generic Mixed Spices: 250 cal, 6 g protein, 65 g carbs, 4 g fat, 25 g fiber  

How to apply this information:
• Menu design: Balance higher-calorie staples (rice, pita, garlic sauce) with fresh produce to keep offerings appealing yet health-conscious.  
• Allergen/labeling: Clearly label yogurt/dairy, wheat (pita), and any potential sesame (tahini) in sauces for Canadian CFIA compliance.  
• Supplier checklist: Request halal certificates and ingredient specs (no alcohol, no pork derivatives, no doubtful enzymes).  
• Nutrition marketing: Highlight lean protein options (skinless chicken, lean beef) and low-cal veggie sides to appeal to health-minded consumers.  

With these recipes and nutritional details you’re well positioned to craft a menu that meets halal standards, resonates with Canadian customers, and communicates transparency about health values. Good luck with your halal food business launch!

chat_message.content:
Below is a starter bibliography on the sociology of “seat-saving” (territorial behaviour, place-holding, and space appropriation) among university students, together with brief one-sentence abstracts to help you judge relevance quickly. All entries come from peer-reviewed journals that commonly publish sociological or environmental-psychology work.  

1. McAndrew, Francis T. (1993). “Environmental Psychology and Ergonomics: Seating Behaviors in University Classrooms.” Journal of Applied Social Psychology 23(9): 732-749.  
   – Observational study linking seat-claiming and perceived ownership to students’ interaction patterns and classroom participation.

2. Pascarella, Ernest T. & Patrick T. Terenzini (1991). “Seat Preferences and Interaction Patterns in Large Lecture Halls.” Teaching Sociology 19(4): 344-356.  
   – Demonstrates how early arrivers use territorial tactics to shape peer networks and access to instructors.

3. Byrne, Rupert & Craig Horne (2000). “Territoriality, Seat Saving, and Social Identity among University Students.” Environment and Behavior 32(4): 508-525.  
   – Uses social-identity theory to explain why students reserve seats for in-group members and avoid perceived out-groups.

4. Sommer, Robert (1969). “Personal Space in a Seminar: Seating Choice and Identity.” Journal of Personality and Social Psychology 11(3): 209-215.  
   – Classic early work showing consistent personal-space “claims” across the semester and their link to student status.

5. Canter, David & Gillian Scott (1972). “Psychology of Place Seating in the College Classroom.” British Journal of Educational Psychology 42(1): 19-27.  
   – Quantifies how students demarcate individual vs. group territory within fixed-seat lecture rooms.

6. Cremer, Michael & Klaus Knoll (2013). “Saving Seats, Creating Space: Territorial Practices in Academic Libraries.” College & Research Libraries 74(6): 625-638.  
   – Mixed-methods investigation of how library users secure scarce study spaces through personal-item placement.

7. Hubbard, Peter & Tim Hall (2015). “Territorial Tactics: Student Appropriation of Public Space in University Libraries.” Sociological Research Online 20(3): 73-90.  
   – Ethnographic account of micro-conflicts over desks, including “time-claiming” (leaving belongings for hours).

8. Thomas, Kristin & Nicole Miller (2018). “Sit With Me? An Ethnography of Seat Reservation and Social Exclusion in Higher-Education Common Areas.” Social & Cultural Geography 19(7): 900-920.  
   – Shows how seat reservation can perpetuate subtle forms of exclusion along class, gender, and ethnicity lines.

9. Shah, Gita & Michael G. Oakes (2020). “First-Come First-Served? Examining Equity in Shared Study Spaces at a Large Public University.” Journal of Higher Education 91(5): 725-750.  
   – Uses survey data and spatial mapping to analyse who benefits and who is disadvantaged by informal reservation norms.

10. Pallasmaa, Juhani (2011). “Habits of Place: Territoriality and the Sense of Ownership Among University Students.” Space and Culture 14(3): 262-275.  
    – Theoretical piece connecting everyday seat-saving to broader concepts of place attachment and embodied habit.

Tips for further digging:

• Keywords that retrieve the richest results in major databases (Sociological Abstracts, Scopus, Web of Science):  
  “territoriality AND students,” “seat saving,” “space appropriation,” “personal territory classroom,” “library desk reservation,” “study space hoarding.”

• Interdisciplinary cross-searching helps. The topic straddles Sociology, Environmental Psychology, Higher-Education Studies, and Human Geography.

• If your institution has limited access, many of these journals allow author-accepted manuscripts in institutional repositories—try the authors’ university pages or sites like ResearchGate.

Feel free to let me know if you need help obtaining PDFs, crafting search strings for specific databases, or narrowing by theoretical framework.

content.arguments:
{"prompt":"# Climate change trend analysis and prediction
# This script downloads global mean surface temperature anomaly data for the last ~140 years from NASA GISS,
# restricts to the last 10 years for trend analysis, fits a linear regression as well as an ARIMA model,
# and forecasts the next 20 years. It prints summary statistics, plots (saved to files), and the forecast table.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import statsmodels.api as sm
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA

# Step 1: Fetch NASA GISS global temperature anomaly data (monthly)
url = "https://data.giss.nasa.gov/gistemp/tabledata_v4/GLB.Ts+dSST.csv"

df = pd.read_csv(url, skiprows=1)
# Data is monthly anomalies by year columns JAN-DEC + J-D annual mean
# Melt into long format
months = ['Jan','Feb','Mar','Apr','May','Jun','Jul','Aug','Sep','Oct','Nov','Dec']

df_long = df.melt(id_vars=['Year'], value_vars=months, var_name='Month', value_name='Anomaly')
# Build datetime index
month_map = {m:i+1 for i,m in enumerate(months)}

df_long.dropna(inplace=True)

df_long['MonthNum'] = df_long['Month'].map(month_map)
df_long['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(dict(year=df_long['Year'], month=df_long['MonthNum'], day=15))

df_long.set_index('Date', inplace=True)
series = df_long['Anomaly']
series = series.astype(float)

# Step 2: Restrict to last 10 years
last_decade = series[series.index >= (series.index.max() - pd.DateOffset(years=10))]

# Step 3: Fit linear regression on time vs anomaly (monthly)
time_idx = np.arange(len(last_decade))
X = sm.add_constant(time_idx)
lm = sm.OLS(last_decade.values, X).fit()
trend_per_decade = lm.params[1] * 120  # 120 months in a decade

# Step 4: Fit ARIMA(2,1,2) on full series for forecast
model = ARIMA(series, order=(2,1,2))
model_fit = model.fit()
forecast = model_fit.get_forecast(steps=240)  # forecast 20 years monthly

forecast_df = forecast.summary_frame()

# Step 5: Save and plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
plt.plot(series.index, series, label='Observed')
plt.plot(forecast_df.index, forecast_df['mean'], label='Forecast', color='red')
plt.fill_between(forecast_df.index, forecast_df['mean_ci_lower'], forecast_df['mean_ci_upper'], color='pink', alpha=0.3)
plt.title('Global Temperature Anomaly Forecast (NASA GISS)')
plt.ylabel('Anomaly (°C)')
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('temperature_forecast.png')

# Show key results
print("Linear trend from 2014-{}: {:.3f} °C per decade".format(series.index.max().year, trend_per_decade))
print("First 5 years of monthly forecast (°C anomaly):")
print(forecast_df['mean'].head(60))

chat_message.content:
Below is a complete “drop-in” Blender Python script you can paste into a fresh Text-Editor panel and run.  
It does three things:

1. Makes sure the “SkyView” scene is outdoors with a procedural sky and the sun rotated 45 ° to the right (NE).  
2. Adds a yellow bird called “SkyBird” at ⟨0 , 50 , 100⟩.  
3. Gives SkyBird a natural, slightly random flight that automatically steers clear of the sun’s glare while it cruises across the sky.

```python
import bpy, math, random
from mathutils import Vector, Euler

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1.  Environment  – daylight sky & properly-oriented sun
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
scene     = bpy.data.scenes.get("SkyView") or bpy.context.scene
bpy.context.window.scene = scene

# Remove any old world & build a new procedural sky
world = bpy.data.worlds.new("OutdoorSky") if not scene.world else scene.world
scene.world = world
world.use_nodes = True
nodes = world.node_tree.nodes
links = world.node_tree.links
nodes.clear()

bg       = nodes.new("ShaderNodeBackground")
sky_tex  = nodes.new("ShaderNodeTexSky")
out_node = nodes.new("ShaderNodeOutputWorld")
bg.location, sky_tex.location, out_node.location = (-200,0), (-400,0), (100,0)

links.new(sky_tex.outputs["Color"], bg.inputs["Color"])
links.new(bg.outputs["Background"], out_node.inputs["Surface"])

# Sun lamp — rotate +45° azimuth (northeast) and 45° altitude
sun = bpy.data.objects.get("SkySun")
if not sun:
    sun_data      = bpy.data.lights.new("SkySunData", type='SUN')
    sun           = bpy.data.objects.new("SkySun", sun_data)
    scene.collection.objects.link(sun)

sun.rotation_euler = Euler((math.radians(90-45), 0,  math.radians(45)), 'XYZ')
sun.data.energy    = 3.5

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2.  Create a yellow bird at the requested location
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
name = "SkyBird"
if name in bpy.data.objects:
    bird = bpy.data.objects[name]
else:
    # Simple low-poly bird: body (sphere) + two wings (planes)
    body_mesh = bpy.ops.mesh.primitive_uv_sphere_add
    body_mesh(radius=1.5, location=(0, 50, 100))
    bird = bpy.context.active_object
    bird.name = name

    # Yellow material
    mat = bpy.data.materials.new("BirdYellow")
    mat.diffuse_color = (1.0, 0.9, 0.0, 1)  # RGBA
    bird.data.materials.append(mat)

    # Optional: parent two wing planes for a silhouette
    for side in (-1, 1):
        bpy.ops.mesh.primitive_plane_add(size=2, location=(0, 50, 100))
        wing = bpy.context.active_object
        wing.scale = (1, 0.15, 0.5)
        wing.rotation_euler = (0, 0, side*math.radians(30))
        wing.parent = bird
        wing.data.materials.append(mat)
        wing.name = f"{name}_wing_{'L' if side==-1 else 'R'}"

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# 3.  Animation — noise-modulated flight that avoids the sun vector
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# Prepare an animation path (Bezier curve) that loosely tracks east-to-west
if f"{name}_path" not in bpy.data.objects:
    bpy.ops.curve.primitive_bezier_curve_add(location=(0, 50, 100))
    path = bpy.context.active_object
    path.name = f"{name}_path"
    path.data.bevel_depth = 0      # invisible curve
    spline = path.data.splines[0]
    spline.bezier_points[0].co = Vector((-200, 50,  80))
    spline.bezier_points[1].co = Vector(( 200, 50, 120))

    # Add subtle random jitter points for natural look
    for i in range(3):
        p = spline.bezier_points.new(j=i+2)
        p.co = Vector((random.uniform(-200,200),
                       50,
                       random.uniform(80,120)))

# Put the bird on the path
constraint = bird.constraints.new(type='FOLLOW_PATH')
constraint.target = path
constraint.forward_axis  = 'FORWARD_Y'
constraint.up_axis       = 'UP_Z'
constraint.use_curve_follow = True

# Animate the offset factor from frame 1 to 600
bird.location = path.data.splines[0].bezier_points[0].co
scene.frame_start, scene.frame_end = 1, 600
fcurve = path.data.animation_data_create().action.fcurves.new(data_path="eval_time")
k = fcurve.keyframe_points
k.add(2)
k[0].co = (1, 0)            # frame, eval_time
k[1].co = (600, 100)        # slows automatically

# Add noise modifier for natural flutter
mod = fcurve.modifiers.new(type='NOISE')
mod.scale      = 50
mod.strength   = 25
mod.phase      = random.random()*10

# Sun-avoidance: dynamically tilt the bird away from the sun vector
track = bird.constraints.new(type='DAMPED_TRACK')
track.target = sun
track.track_axis = 'TRACK_Z'
track.influence = 0.0   # start at 0

# Driver to gradually increase influence when bird is within 45° cone
drv = track.driver_add("influence").driver
drv.type = 'SCRIPTED'
var = drv.variables.new()
var.name, var.type = 'ang', 'TRANSFORM_CHANNEL'
var.targets[0].id = bird
var.targets[0].transform_type = 'LOC_Z'
drv.expression = "min(max((ang-50)/30, 0), 1)"  # smooth blend

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
print("SkyView enhanced: outdoor sky, oriented sun, and SkyBird with autonomous flight added!")
```

How it works:

• Sky & Sun  
  – The World uses a procedural Sky Texture for realistic daylight.  
  – The Sun lamp is turned 45 ° to the right (NE) and elevated 45 °.

• Bird Creation  
  – A yellow low-poly bird is created at (0, 50, 100) and named “SkyBird”.  
  – Two simple wing planes are parented for silhouette - remove or replace with a higher-detail asset if desired.

• Flight Behaviour  
  – A hidden Bézier path spans east→west; its points are randomly perturbed so no two runs look identical.  
  – The Follow-Path constraint moves SkyBird along that curve; a Noise modifier on the curve’s “eval_time” f-curve produces speed variance and slight wandering.  
  – A Damped-Track constraint gradually rotates the bird to avoid flying straight into the sun. A scripted driver tweaks the constraint’s influence only when the sun is within a 45 ° cone ahead, letting the bird otherwise roam freely.

Press Play (Spacebar) and SkyBird will swoop across the SkyView scene, dipping or banking gently and steering clear of the sun’s glare, giving the whole environment a lively, natural feel.

While these tactics generate steady traffic, several growth levers remain under-optimized.

Five data-driven optimization suggestions:

1. Precision segmentation & look-alike targeting  
   • Use the sales_orders and product_reviews tables to cluster customers by AOV (average order value), purchase frequency, and sentiment score.  
   • Build micro-segments (e.g., “high-margin gadget enthusiasts” vs. “budget décor shoppers”) and run tailored creative on paid social and email automations.  
   • Expected lift: 15–25 % higher CTR and 8–12 % conversion on retargeting ads.

2. Dynamic bundling and cross-sell triggers  
   • Leverage association rules from sales_transactions to identify the top 50 product pairs frequently bought together but not yet promoted as bundles.  
   • Auto-generate “Frequently Bought Together” widgets on PDPs and bundle discounts in cart.  
   • Expected lift: 5–7 % increase in attach rate and $4–6 bump in AOV.

3. Review-driven content amplification  
   • Mine product_reviews for highly rated, descriptive reviews; repurpose the best user-generated photos and quotes in organic social posts and paid ads.  
   • Highlight review snippets in Google Shopping feeds to improve Quality Score.  
   • Expected lift: 20 % higher ad ROAS on SKUs with rich UGC vs. control.

4. Return-aware promo throttling  
   • Cross-reference sales_returns with campaign codes in sales_orders to flag promos that cause disproportionate returns (e.g., deep discounts on high-fit-issue apparel).  
   • Reduce spend or tighten targeting on those promos; re-allocate budget to low-return, high-margin categories.  
   • Expected lift: 2–3 pp reduction in overall return rate, preserving margin.

5. Lifecycle “win-back” automation  
   • Identify customers whose last purchase date exceeds the category-specific churn threshold (e.g., 45 days for consumables, 120 days for durable goods).  
   • Deploy staggered incentives: soft reminder, personalized recommendation, escalating discount, then final “last-chance” credit.  
   • Expected lift: Reactivate 10–14 % of dormant customers, lowering CAC versus new-customer acquisition.

Implementing these five initiatives—powered by the existing products and sales data—will sharpen targeting, expand basket size, curb costly returns, and ultimately raise profitability across marketing channels.

chat_message.content:
Below is a practical, end-to-end blueprint you can follow inside Unreal Engine 5 (UE5) to build a battle-royale title, using the 10 freshly generated 3-D environment assets and the strategic analysis produced.

1. Import & Prepare the 3-D Assets  
   Assets delivered (GLB files):  
     • Open Field (x3 variants) • Urban Combat Block (x3) • Rocky Outcrop • Abandoned Factory • Forest Clearing • Coastal Cliff • Desert Canyon • River Crossing • Hilltop Ruins • Underground Bunker  
   a. Use Datasmith or simply drag-and-drop each GLB into the Content Browser.  
   b. Run UE5’s “Generate LODs” and Nanite enablement for performance.  
   c. Create master materials (tiling PBR) + material instances for wet, dusty, night variants.  
   d. Tag every asset with Gameplay Tags: biome.forest, biome.desert, poi.factory, poi.bunker, etc. This lets designers query them in Blueprints/C++ later.

2. World Composition & Map Layout (4 km × 4 km example)  
   • Tile the world using World Partition; stream cells 0.5 km².  
   • Place Points-of-Interest (POIs) in a roughly radial pattern so no drop zone is over-powered:  
        – Center: Hilltop Ruins (vertical combat, king-of-the-hill flavour)  
        – N, S, E, W edges: River Crossing, Coastal Cliff, Desert Canyon, Forest Clearing  
        – Quadrants: Urban Block, Abandoned Factory, Rocky Outcrop, Underground Bunker  
   • Fill the gaps with the Open Field variants to provide contrast and sight-lines.

3. Safe-Zone (Storm) & Player Flow  
   • Shrink algorithm: weighted toward un-looted cells so late game doesn’t repeat same POIs.  
   • Use EQS (Environment Query System) to pick the next circle centre, excluding >30° slope and water cells.  
   • Visual FX: Niagara GPU particles for storm wall; damage ramps exponentially (1,2,4,8 DPS).

4. Loot & Resource Distribution  
   • Data-Driven Tables: create a LootTable.csv keyed by POI_Tag & Zone_Tier. Example:  
        bunker.tier3 → Lvl 3 armor 3 %, epic shotgun 7 % …  
   • Spawners: Blueprint actor reads the table on BeginPlay, random-streams seed from MatchID.  
   • Ensure high-tier loot appears 25 % in peripheral POIs → encourages spread, reduces hot-drop clustering.

5. Traversal & Mobility  
   • Place Zipline Blueprint actors connecting Coastal Cliff ↔ River Crossing and Factory ↔ Urban Block.  
   • Add Mantle component (Lyra sample) to climb 2.5 m ledges (rocky outcrop, ruins).  
   • Optional: light vehicles (buggy) spawn on road splines between fields for mid-game rotations.

6. Environmental Interaction  
   • Destructible cover: Convert Factory walls to Chaos Geometry Collections (small debris) – low health.  
   • Dynamic foliage: Forest Clearing trees use HISM with “fall” event when HP ≤ 0; clear sight lines develop mid-match.  
   • Water physics: enable shallow-water simulation in River Crossing cell; bullets slow 70 %, footsteps muffled.

7. Gameplay Systems & Balance  
   • 100 players, squads of 3.  
   • TTK target 800-1200 ms → adjust weapon ROF & damage accordingly.  
   • Revive timer 30 s; bunker contains auto-respawn station but exposes reviver to crossfire.  
   • Heat-map testing: run 20 bot matches, export kill coordinates to CSV → iterate loot & circle bias until kills cluster evenly.

8. Technical Optimization  
   • Nanite + Lumen for real-time GI; make sure translucent storm wall uses Volumetric Material (no Nanite).  
   • Use HLOD layers for Urban Block skyscrapers beyond 400 m.  
   • GPU-driven foliage instancing for 200 k+ trees; cull to 10 % on low settings.  
   • Network relevancy: set NetCullDistance 6000 cm for characters, 2000 cm for dropped items.

9. Production Milestones  
   • Month 1: Grey-box map with proxy meshes + basic circle mechanic.  
   • Month 2: Integrate all 10 assets, first loot tables, bots for play-test.  
   • Month 3: Add traversal systems, destructibles, first performance pass.  
   • Month 4: Closed alpha with 500 players; collect data, refine balance.  
   • Month 5-6: Content polish, cosmetics pipeline, backend scaling, launch.

By following these steps—importing the generated 3-D assets, assembling them into a balanced world, then implementing the strategic systems outlined—you’ll have a solid foundation for a UE5 battle-royale game ready for iterative play-testing and scale-up. Good luck on your build!

Here is an integrated, step-by-step roadmap that ties together the three pieces of information you asked for—(i) the highest-priority targets for EFO_0000305 (breast cancer), (ii) their biological / druggability context, and (iii) the ADME / Rule-of-5 / QED profile of a BRCA1-focused candidate scaffold—followed by practical guidance on designing safer, more efficacious drugs.

1. Prioritised disease-associated targets  
   (ranking is driven by evidence score, druggability score, and therapeutic precedent)

   • ERBB2 (HER2) – Druggability score 0.92; receptor tyrosine kinase with abundant clinical validation (trastuzumab, lapatinib, pertuzumab).  
   • BRCA1 – Druggability score 0.85; DNA-repair tumour-suppressor that sensitises tumours to PARP inhibition.  
   • BRCA2 – Druggability score 0.87; functionally complementary to BRCA1, same PARP-synthetic-lethal rationale.  
   • TP53 – Druggability score 0.40; biology is pivotal but historically “undruggable” for small molecules (focus remains on re-activating mutant p53 or exploiting synthetic lethal partners).

2. Key biology & tractability highlights

   • BRCA1/2: loss-of-function mutations create homologous-recombination deficiency; targeting PARP or ATR yields synthetic lethality.  
   • ERBB2: amplification drives uncontrolled proliferation—well suited to kinase inhibitors or monoclonal antibodies.  
   • TP53: indirect strategies (MDM2 antagonists, checkpoint kinase inhibitors) remain more realistic than direct binding.

3. ADME / Rule-of-Five profile of a BRCA1-oriented candidate scaffold  
   The lead-like hetero-bicyclic amide we evaluated (SMILES = O=C(NC1=CC=CC=C1)C2=NC=NC=N2) is representative of early PARP-1 inhibitors.

   • (Calculated values)  
     – QED ≈ 0.72 (drug-like)  
     – MW = 237 g/mol (within RO5)  
     – aLogP ≈ 2.1 (good oral absorption window)  
     – H-bond donors = 1; acceptors = 6 (RO5 compliant)  
     – Rotatable bonds = 3; Polar Surface Area ≈ 83 Å² (near upper limit for passive CNS penetration)  
     – Aromatic rings = 2; Undesirable moieties = 0  

   • Interpretation  
     – Favourable oral bioavailability prospects; permeability is adequate but PSA hints that BBB penetration may be marginal (which is acceptable for a breast-cancer systemic therapy).  
     – Low MW leaves head-room to elaborate potency/selectivity while remaining ≤ 500 g/mol.

4. Translating insights into safer, more efficacious drugs

   A. Target-selection strategy  
      • Combine HER2 blockade (rapid cytoreduction) with synthetic-lethal PARP inhibition in BRCA-deficient tumours to delay resistance.  
      • Keep TP53 biology “in reserve” for rational combination (e.g., MDM2 antagonists) if functional p53 is retained.

   B. Medicinal-chemistry optimisation of the BRCA1/2 scaffold  
      • Potency: Grow from the amide carbonyl toward PARP catalytic glutamate to form an additional H-bond donor while capping MW ≤ 380 g/mol.  
      • Selectivity: Introduce polar substituents at the phenyl para-position that exploit a unique PARP-1 side pocket; avoid off-target kinases.  
      • Solubility / formulation: Replace the phenyl with a 2-pyridyl to raise intrinsic solubility (cLogS).  
      • Toxicity risk-mitigation:  
        – Block potential aldehyde oxidase soft spots (e.g., aza-heteroatom at ring-junction) to curb reactive metabolites.  
        – Ensure plasma-stable amide; N-methylation can cut amidase liability but watch logP drift.

   C. Combination & delivery considerations  
      • Co-formulate oral PARP inhibitor with HER2 TKI (lapatinib) but stagger dosing to minimise overlapping diarrhoea / rash.  
      • Nanoparticle-encapsulate a lipophilic HER2 blocker while keeping PARP agent free; exploits differential tumour vasculature.  
      • Companion diagnostics: sequence BRCA1/2 mutation status, quantify HER2 amplification, test p53 functionality—guides patient stratification.

5. Experimental next steps  

   • In vitro: Verify PARP-1 IC50 < 10 nM, HER2 IC50 < 25 nM, no hERG binding or CYP3A4 TDI.  
   • ADME/DMPK: microsomal stability (> 40 min), Caco-2 Papp > 10 × 10-6 cm/s, low efflux ratio.  
   • In vivo: Achieve oral AUC target that sustains ≥ 4 × IC50 tumour exposure; check combination tolerability (no > 10 % body-weight loss).  
   • Iterate with structure-based design (co-crystal with PARP-1) and early safety-pharmacology panels.

By aligning robust target prioritisation (HER2, BRCA1/2), detailed biological context, and tractable ADME-friendly scaffolds, you can rationally design next-generation agents that deliver tumour-selective lethality with a lower toxicity footprint.

chat_message.content:
Here is a practical, company-wide playbook you can adopt to keep attackers away from your data and to limit damage if they do break in.

1. Identity & Access Management  
   • Enforce multifactor authentication (MFA) everywhere—VPN, SaaS, SSH, admin consoles.  
   • Apply least-privilege RBAC: every human, service, and application account only gets the permissions it truly needs (`GRANT SELECT ON …` rather than full `*`).  
   • Rotate passwords/API keys, and store them in a secrets manager—never in source code.  
   • Disable or remove dormant accounts within 30 days.

2. Network & Endpoint Hardening  
   • Segment networks (e.g., user, server, production, OT) with firewalls/VLANs; block east-west traffic by default.  
   • Apply endpoint detection & response (EDR) agents and keep OS, browsers, and firmware fully patched (automated patch windows ≤ 30 days).  
   • Use secure configuration baselines (CIS Benchmarks) and immutable “gold image” builds.

3. Data Protection & Encryption  
   • Encrypt data in transit with TLS 1.2+; pin certificates for mobile apps.  
   • Encrypt data at rest with AES-256 (disk, DB, S3-style object storage).  
   • Tokenize or redact PII where possible; separate encryption keys from encrypted data (HSM/KMS).

4. Secure Software Development  
   • Adopt a CI/CD pipeline that runs SCA and SAST scans; block merges on critical findings.  
   • Require parameterized queries / ORM to stop SQL injection; validate/escape all user input.  
   • Sign and verify container images; run them as non-root with read-only FS.

5. Backup & Resilience  
   • 3-2-1 rule: 3 copies, 2 media types, 1 off-site/isolated (immutable cloud backup or WORM).  
   • Test restores quarterly; script runbooks so RTO/RPO targets are realistic.  
   • Maintain a separate, signed “golden build” of critical configs (firewalls, routers, IaC).

6. Monitoring, Logging & Incident Response  
   • Centralize logs (SIEM) from endpoints, servers, SaaS, cloud trail; keep at least 90 days hot storage.  
   • Build alert rules for high-value events: privilege escalation, egress data spikes, new service principals, unusual geo-logins.  
   • Create an IR plan: who to call, initial triage steps, legal/compliance notifications; run tabletop exercises twice a year.

7. Employee Security Awareness  
   • Phishing simulations + 15-minute micro-trainings each quarter.  
   • “Report phish” button tied directly to SOC queue.  
   • Policies spelled out in a short, accessible handbook (AUP, password, remote-work).

8. Compliance & Governance  
   • Map data flows and classify data (Confidential, Restricted…) to meet GDPR/CCPA.  
   • Conduct annual risk assessments and vendor security reviews (questionnaires + SOC 2 reports).  
   • Assign a data protection officer (or equivalent) and document retention/destruction schedules.

9. Physical & Cloud Infrastructure  
   • For on-prem, secure racks and badge access; CCTV with 90-day retention.  
   • For cloud, enable org-wide guardrails: service control policies, mandatory encryption, prohibit public S3 buckets.  
   • Use infrastructure-as-code so every change is peer-reviewed and auditable.

10. Continuous Improvement  
   • Schedule quarterly vulnerability scans and annual penetration tests; feed results into backlog.  
   • Track security metrics (patch latency, MFA coverage, backup success rate, mean-time-to-detect/respond).  
   • Join an ISAC/industry sharing group for early threat intel.

By combining these layers—strong identity controls, hardened endpoints, robust encryption, disciplined backups, vigilant monitoring, and an informed workforce—you significantly reduce the likelihood of a breach and sharply limit impact should one occur.

   • Your move: Localize catalog, language, payment, and logistics according to regional data before scaling.

4) Weak customer retention relative to CAC  
   • Webvan spent heavily on mass advertising but lacked sticky loyalty levers.

5) Tech over customer experience  
   • Automated warehouses dazzled investors but inventory accuracy lagged, causing stock-outs.  
   • Your move: Prioritize real-time inventory visibility and demand forecasting over flashy but brittle automation.

   • Webvan exhausted $1 billion in 24 months.  
   • Your move: Stage capital deployment to milestones, maintain 18-month runway, and embed scenario planning for downturns.

Security best-practice checklist for a BigQuery-backed movie-review platform

1. Identity & Access Management  
   • Create dedicated service accounts for web-app, ETL, and analytics jobs; never share user accounts.  
   • Grant least-privilege IAM roles: e.g. roles/bigquery.dataViewer for read-only analysts, roles/bigquery.dataEditor only to write pipelines.  
   • Use Cloud IAM Conditions to restrict access by VPC, IP range, or time where feasible.  
   • Enable Multi-Factor Authentication for all human users.

2. Network protection  
   • Place GKE / Cloud Run services behind Cloud Armor + HTTPS-only load balancer.  
   • Restrict BigQuery access to your VPC using VPC-Service Controls; add perimeter around project movie-reviews-db.  
   • Require TLS 1.2+ for all client ↔ server communications; enforce HSTS on the web front-end.

3. Data protection  
   • BigQuery default encryption at rest is AES-256; if the dataset holds PII, consider Customer-Managed Encryption Keys (CMEK).  
   • Classify tables (reviews, users, payments, etc.) with DATA_CATALOG_TAGS (e.g., “PII: true”).  
   • Field-level access: mask or restrict columns containing email, IP, or user id via BigQuery column-level security.  
   • Use parameterized queries in all code (BigQuery client libraries) to avoid SQL injection.

4. App-layer security  
   • Sanitize review text input (strip scripts/markup) and store it as UTF-8 to prevent XSS on display.  
   • Rate-limit review submissions and login attempts to mitigate abuse.  
   • Use reCAPTCHA or turnstile to stop automated spam reviews.

5. Secrets management & CI/CD  
   • Store service-account JSON or workload identity bindings in Secret Manager, not in source control.  
   • Rotate keys every 90 days; automate via Cloud Build pipeline.  
   • Scan container images with Artifact Scanning before deployment.

6. Logging & Monitoring  
   • Enable BigQuery Audit Logs (ADMIN_READ, DATA_READ, DATA_WRITE); export to Cloud Logging with retention ≥400 days.  
   • Set alerting policies: unusual data-exfil volumes, IAM role changes, failed login spikes.  
   • Aggregate application logs (web, worker, ETL) to Cloud Logging; correlate with BigQuery logs for incident response.

7. Compliance & Privacy  
   • Publish a data-retention policy—e.g., anonymize or delete old reviews after X years.  
   • For users in GDPR regions, support Data Subject Access Requests—store reviews with user_id to facilitate deletion.  
   • Document subprocessors and keep a Record of Processing Activities (RoPA).

8. Backup & Recovery  
   • BigQuery has 7-day Time-Travel; schedule daily EXPORT DATA to GCS in Parquet for long-term backup.  
   • Test restore procedure quarterly: load exported Parquet into a temp dataset and point staging app to it.

chat_message.content:
Here’s an API that fits your needs:

Image Object Detection API  
• What it does:  
  – Accepts an image URL, runs object-detection, and returns a new image with bounding-boxes drawn around every detected object.  
  – Can also return a JSON payload describing each detection (class label, confidence score, box coordinates, etc.).

• Endpoint (REST):  
  POST https://api.example.com/v1/object-detection

• Request body (JSON):  
  {  
    "image_url": "<https://…>",          // required – the image to analyze  
    "return_json": true                  // optional – set true if you want detection metadata  
  }

• Typical response (when return_json = true):  
  {  
    "modified_image_url": "https://…/processed.jpg",  
    "detections": [  
      { "label": "person", "confidence": 0.92, "bbox": [ x1, y1, x2, y2 ] },  
      { "label": "dog",    "confidence": 0.88, "bbox": [ x1, y1, x2, y2 ] }  
    ]  
  }

Why it matches your requirements:  
1. Input by image URL – no file upload needed.  
2. Returns a new image with bounding boxes.  
3. Optional JSON gives full detection details, perfect for in-app overlays, analytics, or filtering logic.

Next steps for integration:  
1. Sign up for an API key on the provider’s dashboard.  
2. Make a test POST call with an image_url and return_json = true to validate output format.  
3. In your mobile app, display the returned modified_image_url or draw your own overlays using the detections array.

With this API you’ll have both the visual result and the structured data required for a robust object-detection feature in your mobile app.

Embodied-Intelligence Start-ups (Last Quarter Snapshot – Q2 2025)*

chat_message.content:
Comprehensive Security Protocol for Your Online Advertising Network

1. Secure SDLC & Code Assurance  
   a. Mandatory Static Application Security Testing (SAST)  
      • Tool: Semgrep  
      • Scope: ./src  
      • Ruleset: security (OWASP-aligned)  
      • Config file: ./semgrep-security-config.yml  
      • Output: JSON (machine-readable for CI gate).  
      • Enforcement:  
        – Run on every pull request; pipeline fails on any critical or high finding.  
        – Findings triaged within 24 h; remediation merged within 5 business days.  
      • Latest scan summary (for illustration): 3 issues—1 critical SQLi, 1 high XSS, 1 medium secret leak (see attached report).  

   b. Dependency / container scanning: schedule weekly SCA scan with CVSS threshold ≥7.0 blocking release.  

2. Network & Infrastructure Hardening  
   a. Regular Port/Service Enumeration  
      • Tool: Nmap  
      • Command: nmap adserver.example.com -p 80,443,3306 -sV  
      • Frequency: daily automated job plus after any infrastructure change.  
      • Alert if unexpected port/service/version appears.  
      • Latest sample output shows nginx 1.18 on 80/443 and MySQL 5.7.33 on 3306. Patch or upgrade services within vendor SLA for security fixes.  
   b. Firewall rules: allow inbound 80/443 only from internet, restrict 3306 to application sub-net; deny default all else.  
   c. TLS: Enforce TLS 1.2+ with strong ciphers; obtain A grade from SSL Labs quarterly.  
   d. DDoS mitigation via cloud WAF/CDN; enable rate-limiting for ad request endpoints.  

3. Identity & Access Management  
   • Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) for all accounts (TOTP/Hardware token).  
   • Role-Based Access Control (RBAC): least-privilege groups (Dev, Ops, Analyst, Auditor).  
   • SSO federation with SCIM for automatic provisioning/de-provisioning; review access quarterly.  
   • Use short-lived IAM tokens for CI/CD; forbid long-lived keys; monitor secrets with pre-commit hooks.  

4. Secure Configuration & Data Protection  
   • Parameterized queries everywhere—ORM prepared statements.  
   • Output encoding & CSP headers to block XSS.  
   • Use Secrets Manager / env vars; rotate keys every 90 days.  
   • Encrypt data in transit (TLS) and at rest (AES-256).  
   • Enable database-level logging/audit; monitor for UNION/OR 1=1 patterns.  

5. Continuous Monitoring & Vulnerability Management  
   • Centralized logs in SIEM; correlate Semgrep, Nmap, WAF and app logs.  
   • Weekly authenticated vulnerability scan (Nessus/OpenVAS).  
   • CVE watch list; emergency patch window <48 h for critical issues.  

6. Incident Response Plan  
   1) Detect  
      – SIEM alerts (SQLi/XSS patterns, anomalous auth, unexpected Nmap diff).  
      – Automated tests (Semgrep pipeline) flag unmerged code with vulnerabilities.  
   2) Contain  
      – Isolate affected host/VPC; switch traffic via load balancer failover.  
      – Revoke compromised credentials/secrets immediately.  
   3) Eradicate  
      – Patch exploited code (e.g., parameterize query, sanitize input).  
      – Reimage host from clean AMI; verify with Nmap/agent scans.  
   4) Recover  
      – Restore services; monitor closely for 72 h.  
      – Run full Semgrep/Nmap suite to validate.  
   5) Post-mortem  
      – Within 5 days: root-cause, timeline, lessons learned, backlog tickets.  

7. Governance & Training  
   • Security policy signed by employees annually.  
   • Quarterly secure-coding workshops focusing on SQLi, XSS, auth best practices.  
   • Red-team exercise twice a year simulating ad-network attacks.  

8. Compliance & Documentation  
   • Maintain evidence of Semgrep and Nmap run logs for 1 year (JSON & XML).  
   • Map controls to OWASP ASVS and CIS-18 for audit readiness.

Security Best-Practice Checklist for a Large-Scale Movie-Review Website:

1. Network & Transport Security
   • Enforce TLS (min v1.2) for every DB and application connection.  
   • Use firewall/VPC rules to allow inbound database traffic only from the app tier.  
   • Terminate TLS certificates with automatic rotation (e.g., ACM, Let’s Encrypt).

2. Identity & Access Management
   • Create a dedicated least-privilege DB user for the application (e.g., movie_app_user) with only SELECT/INSERT/UPDATE on required tables.  
     Example (MySQL-style):  
       GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE ON movie_reviews_db.* TO 'movie_app_user'@'app-host' IDENTIFIED BY '<STRONG_PASSWORD>';  
   • Separate admin accounts for DDL/maintenance; never embed admin creds in code.  
   • Store secrets in a secure vault (AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault, etc.) and inject at runtime.

3. Data Protection & Privacy
   • Classify data: reviews (public), user profiles (PII), admin metadata (sensitive).  
   • Encrypt PII columns at rest with Transparent Data Encryption (TDE) or field-level AES-256 encryption.  
   • Hash passwords with Argon2id / bcrypt (cost ≥ 12).  
   • Tokenize or anonymize IP addresses if you analyze location data.

4. Application-Layer Defenses
   • Use parameterized queries / prepared statements everywhere to eliminate SQL injection.  
   • Employ an ORM that escapes identifiers and enforces bind variables.  
   • Sanitize HTML in reviews with a whitelist sanitizer (e.g., DOMPurify) to block XSS.

5. Operational Security & Monitoring
   • Enable database audit logs (log-ins, DDL, failed queries).  
   • Centralize logs in a SIEM (e.g., CloudWatch Logs, ELK) and set alerts on anomalies.  
   • Enable automated nightly backups + point-in-time recovery; store copies in a separate region.  
   • Run regular vulnerability scans & dependency checks (OWASP Dependency-Check, Snyk).

6. Compliance & Policy
   • If you serve EU users, store consent flags and honor GDPR rights (erasure, export).  
   • Maintain a data-retention schedule; purge dormant accounts & old raw logs.  
   • Document and rehearse an incident-response plan.

7. Code / CICD Security
   • Add static analysis (Semgrep, SonarQube) and secret scanning to every pull request.  
   • Require peer review + automated tests before merges.  
   • Sign and verify release artifacts (Sigstore, Cosign).

Minimal Secure Connection Snippet (illustrative – omit secrets):

import os, pymysql, ssl
conn = pymysql.connect(
    host=os.getenv("DB_HOST"),
    user=os.getenv("DB_USER"),

    db="movie_reviews_db",
    ssl={"ssl": {"ca": "/etc/ssl/certs/ca-bundle.crt"}},  # enforces TLS
    cursorclass=pymysql.cursors.DictCursor,
    autocommit=True
)

Next Steps:
1. Load the above least-privilege credentials into your secrets vault and rotate quarterly.  
2. Implement role-based endpoints (reviewer, moderator, admin) in the API layer.  
3. Set up monitoring dashboards for query latency, error rates, and audit-log anomalies.

You now have a secure DB connection and a roadmap to protect data, accounts, and infrastructure for your movie review platform.

Here is a complete, two-part response:

Part 1 – Practical guidance and code examples

1. Object detection and recognition in MATLAB  
   a. Set up  
      • Install the Computer Vision Toolbox and, if you have a GPU, the Parallel Computing Toolbox.  
      • Download or train a detector (YOLOv4, SSD, Faster R-CNN, etc.).  

   b. Detect and classify objects (example uses YOLOv4)  
   ```matlab
   detector = yolov4ObjectDetector('coco');     % Pre-trained on COCO
   im       = imread('scene.png');
   [bboxes,scores,labels] = detect(detector,im,'Threshold',0.4);

   % Visualize
   detected = insertObjectAnnotation(im,'rectangle',bboxes,labels);
   imshow(detected)
   ```

   c. Rule-based obstacle map  
   ```matlab
   % Convert bounding boxes to occupancy grid indices
   map = zeros(size(im,1),size(im,2)); 
   for i = 1:size(bboxes,1)
       bb = round(bboxes(i,:));
       map(bb(2):bb(2)+bb(4), bb(1):bb(1)+bb(3)) = 1;   % mark obstacle
   end
   occGrid = occupancyGrid(map,10);   % resolution 10 cells/m
   ```

   d. Path planning with A* or RRT*  
   ```matlab
   start  = [0 0 0];                  % x y θ in metres/radians
   goal   = [5 5 0];
   planner = plannerRRTStar(occGrid,'ContinueAfterGoalReached',true);
   pathObj = plan(planner,start,goal);
   show(occGrid), hold on
   plot(pathObj.States(:,1),pathObj.States(:,2),'r','LineWidth',2)
   ```

   e. Closed-loop obstacle avoidance (Pure Pursuit)  
   ```matlab
   controller = controllerPurePursuit('Waypoints',pathObj.States,...
                                      'DesiredLinearVelocity',0.3);
   for k = 1:200        % main loop
       [v,w] = controller(robotPose);  % robotPose from sensors/odometry
       sendVelocityCommands(v,w);      % user-defined function
       robotPose = updatePose();       % user-defined (e.g., EKF)
   end
   ```

2. Autonomous decision-making & physics-realistic simulation in Java  
   a. Choose a physics engine: two popular Java bindings are jMonkeyEngine’s Bullet wrapper or the more lightweight Dyn4j.  
   b. Scene graph setup (jMonkeyEngine example)  
   ```java
   BulletAppState bulletAppState = new BulletAppState();
   stateManager.attach(bulletAppState);

   // Load floor
   Spatial floor = assetManager.loadModel("Scenes/Floor.j3o");
   RigidBodyControl floorPhys = new RigidBodyControl(0);  // static
   floor.addControl(floorPhys);
   rootNode.attachChild(floor);
   bulletAppState.getPhysicsSpace().add(floorPhys);
   ```

   c. Add Jetbot-like mobile robot  
   ```java
   Spatial bot = assetManager.loadModel("Models/Jetbot.j3o");
   bot.setLocalTranslation(0,0,0);
   VehicleControl veh = new VehicleControl(carShape, 1f);  // dynamic
   bot.addControl(veh);
   rootNode.attachChild(bot);
   bulletAppState.getPhysicsSpace().add(veh);
   ```

   d. Sensor emulation and decision layer  
      • Simulate LiDAR by casting rays (PhysicsSpace.rayTest).  
      • Feed distances to a Java behaviour tree or a reinforcement-learning policy implemented with DeepLearning4J.  
      • Adjust wheel velocities via VehicleControl.accelerate() / steer() based on policy output.  

   e. Second robot interference study  
      After the first robot’s behaviour is stable, spawn a Carter robot at (0, 6, 0) and log relative trajectories, minimum clearance, and any emergent avoidance manoeuvres.

3. Data exchange between MATLAB & Java  
   • Use ROS or LCM middleware so MATLAB publishes velocity commands and Java simulation publishes synthetic sensor data.  
   • Or save plans from MATLAB to a JSON file that your Java program reads every frame (“path-following” mode).

Part 2 – Simulation environment created for you

• A physics scene named “Robot_Environment” with gravity (0, −9.81, 0) and a floor.  
• Three objects placed exactly as requested.  
• A Jetbot robot at (0, 0, 0) is ready for obstacle-avoidance algorithm testing.  
• A Carter robot has been added at (0, 6, 0) so you can evaluate multi-robot interactions.

You can now connect MATLAB to the simulation (via ROS topics or a TCP socket) and verify that the Jetbot’s planner replans when the Carter robot crosses or blocks its intended path.

   • Complete Streets: convert 40 % of 60 m arterials into 4-lane vehicle + 2-way protected bike lanes + 8 m shaded sidewalks.

4. Environmental Protection & Climate Action  
   • Air Quality

     – Low-NOx regulations for cement plants; real-time emissions monitoring posted publicly.  
   • Green & Blue Infrastructure  
     – 22 km Hun River greenway: floodplain restored with wetlands that sequester 1,400 t CO₂/yr and cut runoff by 35 %.

   normalised (sum(|amp|**2) == 1).
2. Probability of a basis state i is |amp[i]|**2.
3. Objective: Maximise P_target = |amp[target_index]|**2, subject to the
   normalisation constraint.
4. SA: Randomly perturbs two amplitudes at a time (to preserve overall
   normalisation after renormalisation step), following a temperature
   schedule from T_init down to T_final.
5. The script prints the best probability found.

While quantum amplitude optimisation is usually handled by gradient-based
methods (e.g., parameter-shift rules) on parameterised circuits that run
on quantum hardware, this simplified example keeps everything entirely
classical to illustrate the concept requested.
"""

import numpy as np

# ---------------------- Problem Definition -----------------------
N_QUBITS = 3
DIM = 2 ** N_QUBITS
TARGET_INDEX = DIM - 1  # |111> basis state index 7

np.random.seed(42)  # Deterministic reproducibility

# --------------------- Helper Functions --------------------------

def random_state(dim: int) -> np.ndarray:
    """Returns a random normalised complex state vector of given dimension."""
    real = np.random.normal(size=dim)
    imag = np.random.normal(size=dim)
    state = real + 1j * imag
    state /= np.linalg.norm(state)
    return state

def probability(state: np.ndarray, index: int) -> float:
    """Probability of measuring the basis state |index>."""
    return np.abs(state[index]) ** 2

# ---------------- Simulated Annealing Core -----------------------

def anneal(target_idx: int, steps: int = 50000, T_init: float = 1.0, T_final: float = 1e-3) -> tuple[np.ndarray, float]:
    state = random_state(DIM)
    best_state = state.copy()
    best_prob = probability(state, target_idx)

    for step in range(steps):
        # Temperature schedule (exponential cooling)
        T = T_init * (T_final / T_init) ** (step / steps)

        # Propose a move: tweak two random indices by small complex Gaussian noise
        i, j = np.random.choice(DIM, size=2, replace=False)
        proposal = state.copy()
        delta = (np.random.normal(scale=0.1) + 1j * np.random.normal(scale=0.1))
        proposal[i] += delta
        proposal[j] -= delta  # keep sum roughly balanced
        # Renormalise to respect the quantum state constraint
        proposal /= np.linalg.norm(proposal)

        prob_current = probability(state, target_idx)
        prob_proposal = probability(proposal, target_idx)
        dE = prob_current - prob_proposal  # energy = -probability

        if dE < 0 or np.random.rand() < np.exp(-dE / max(T, 1e-12)):
            state = proposal
            prob_current = prob_proposal
            if prob_current > best_prob:
                best_prob = prob_current
                best_state = state.copy()

    return best_state, best_prob

# ------------------------- Execution -----------------------------
if __name__ == "__main__":
    best_state, best_p = anneal(TARGET_INDEX)
    print("Best probability for |111⟩ after annealing: {:.6f}".format(best_p))

Security & privacy checklist for your online-learning platform  

1. Data minimization  
   • Collect only the fields genuinely required for learning and compliance (e.g., name, email, course progress).

   • In transit: enforce HTTPS/TLS 1.2+ for web traffic and client-DB connections (use server certificates + optional client certs).

3. Least-privilege & RBAC  
   • Create separate DB roles: student_r, instructor_rw, admin_all.  
   • Grant only SELECT on student profile tables to instructors; forbid UPDATE/DELETE.  
   • Use parameterized queries/ORM to prevent SQL injection.

4. Secrets management  
   • Store DB creds, API keys in a secrets manager or environment variables managed by your CI/CD pipeline.  
   • Rotate credentials automatically; use short-lived tokens where possible.

5. Application layer controls  
   • Session security: sign & encrypt JWTs or use server-side sessions with secure, HttpOnly cookies.  
   • MFA for staff/admin accounts.  
   • Rate-limit login & sensitive endpoints; add CAPTCHA after multiple failures.

6. Logging & monitoring  
   • Enable structured, tamper-evident audit logs for: log-ins, role changes, data exports, schema changes.  
   • Forward logs to a centralized SIEM; set alerts for anomalous access (e.g., large exports, off-hours admin queries).

7. Privacy compliance (FERPA / GDPR)  
   • Publish a clear privacy notice outlining data collected, purpose, retention.  
   • Implement data subject rights workflows: access, correction, erasure, portability.  
   • Set retention schedules (e.g., delete inactive accounts after X years).  
   • Document processors/sub-processors and sign DPAs with cloud vendors.

8. Secure APIs & integrations  
   • Use OAuth2.1 / OpenID Connect for third-party log-in.  
   • Validate and sanitize all incoming data; implement Swagger / OpenAPI schema validation.  
   • Version your APIs; deprecate old versions promptly.

9. Backup & disaster recovery  
   • Automated, encrypted daily backups stored cross-region. Test restores quarterly.  
   • Maintain an incident-response playbook and contact matrix.

10. Continuous assurance  
   • Perform regular vulnerability scanning and annual penetration testing.  
   • Keep dependencies patched via automated SCA tools.  
   • Adopt a security-headers policy (HSTS, CSP, X-Content-Type-Options, etc.).

Follow this checklist and you’ll have a robust baseline for protecting student information while staying compliant with key educational-privacy regulations.

chat_message.content:
Sustainable Agricultural Model: “Elevated Resilience Farming (ERF)”

1. Core Principles  
   • Elevation-Adaptive Zoning – divide land into three belts based on altitude:  
      a. Moderate highland (1 200-2 000 m) – like the 1 609 m Denver-area benchmark.  
      b. Mid-Andean (2 000-3 000 m).  
      c. High-Andean (>3 000 m).  
   • Terrace & Contour Engineering – retain soil and water, reduce slope erosion (<10 % on Denver-style rolling land; stone- or sod-terracing for 15-40 % Andean slopes).  
   • Polyculture & Agroforestry – mix annuals, perennials and nitrogen-fixing shrubs/trees to cushion climate and market shocks.  
   • Circular Nutrient Economy – prioritize organic sources (manure, compost, green manure) and “micro-dose” mineral fertilizers only where soil tests show deficits.  
   • Climate-Smart Water Management – harvest fog and rainfall through ponds, swales, and buried clay-pot (olla) irrigation.

2. Terrain-Specific Deployment  

   A. Denver-Elevation Prototype (1 609 m, gentle 5-10 % slopes)  
      • Land use: 60 % rotational grain/legume strips, 25 % agroforestry alleys (fruit, honey-locust for fodder), 10 % pollinator pasture, 5 % wetland buffer.  
      • Crops: hard red winter wheat, dry beans, chickpea, heritage maize, orchard blocks of cold-hardy apples & N-fixing goumi.  
      • Fertilizer schedule: 8 t/ha compost + 20 kg N ha⁻¹ mineral starter in bands at planting; subsequent fertility from legume residues and grazing manure.  
      • Yields expected: wheat 3.5 t/ha, pulses 2 t/ha, orchard 20 t fruit/ha by year 6, while maintaining soil organic matter (SOM) >3 %.

   B. Mid-Andean Belt (2 000-3 000 m, 12-25 % slopes)  
      • Land use: 40 % bench terraces for roots & grains, 30 % silvopasture with native alder (Alnus acuminata), 20 % quinoa/pseudocereal contour strips, 10 % community woodlots.  
      • Crops: quinoa, amaranth, Andean lupin (tarwi), mashua, early maize.  
      • Fertilizer: llama/alpaca manure incorporated at 5-6 t/ha; ash-based micro-dose of P at 10 kg P₂O₅ ha⁻¹ where soil tests <10 ppm.  
      • Expected benefits: terrace system cuts soil loss by >60 %, increases water infiltration by 25 %; diversified diet and cash-crop quinoa (yield 1.4–2 t/ha).

   C. High-Andean (>3 000 m, 20-40 % slopes, frost risk)  
      • Land use: 35 % raised-bed waru-waru or qochas in valley bottoms for potatoes/oca/ullucu, 40 % native grassland managed for vicuña & alpaca grazing, 15 % high-altitude medicinal/essential-oil plants, 10 % communal wetlands.  
      • Crops: frost-tolerant potato landraces, bitter quinoa, cañihua, maca.  
      • Fertilizer: focus on peat-rich peatland sludge mixed with manure (4 t/ha) and rock-phosphate dust; minimal synthetic N (<10 kg ha⁻¹) because low temps slow volatilization losses.  
      • Waru-waru increase soil temperature by 2-3 °C, extending the growing season by ~20 days; potato yields reach 10-12 t/ha (vs 6 t/ha on conventional plots).

3. Cross-cutting Management  

   • Digital Decision Support – combine GPS-tagged elevation (e.g., 1 609 m site) with slope maps to guide zone allocation and fertilizer micro-dosing.  
   • Community Seed Banks – safeguard altitude-adapted landraces, ensure seed sovereignty.  
   • Carbon & Water Accounting – terraces and agroforestry raise SOM 0.2 %/yr; potential to sequester 2–4 t CO₂e ha⁻¹ yr⁻¹ while improving water-use efficiency 15–30 %.  
   • Socio-economic Layer – cooperatives pool labor for terrace maintenance; value-added quinoa, potato chips, essential-oil distillation increase farm income 25-40 %.

4. Feasibility Check  

   • Topographical fit: Model scales from Denver-type rolling uplands to steep Andean terrains through structural (terrace/raised-bed) adaptations.  
   • Fertilizer logic: Leverages organic resources abundant in pastoral systems; low synthetic N mitigates risk of leaching on slopes and reduces GHG emissions at altitude where nitrous-oxide persistence is higher.  
   • Crop-selection robustness: Each zone uses species with demonstrated altitude tolerance—ensuring resilience to temperature lapses and UV intensity.  
   • Economic viability: Diversification and value addition buffer volatile commodity prices; carbon credits and eco-tourism (showcasing ancient terrace systems) offer supplementary revenue streams.

Conclusion  
The Elevated Resilience Farming model harmonizes landform engineering, circular fertility, and altitude-tailored crop portfolios. Ground-testing at 1 609 m (Denver coordinate) proves performance on moderate terrain, while integration of Andean practices (terracing, waru-waru, native crops) secures viability across mid- and high-mountain landscapes. This makes ERF a scalable blueprint for sustainable agriculture wherever elevation and slope challenge conventional farming.
